### Feature A1: Split param stream → off_buf + delta_buf → ZXLA

#### Problem
ZXL9 encoded all match parameters (offsets, mtype, delta values) in a single rANS
`param_buf` stream. These populations have different distributions:
  - Offset bytes: spread across 0–255, biased toward smaller values for short-range
    matches. Shared with EXACT and DELTA tokens.
  - mtype bytes: only ever 1 (XOR) or 2 (ADD). Near-zero entropy. Pollutes offset model.
  - Delta value bytes: XOR/additive constants, often 0x04/0x08/0x10/etc for typical
    address deltas. Different distribution from both mtype and offset bytes.
A single rANS model can't simultaneously fit a near-binary mtype, a delta distribution
peaked around small constants, and a broader offset distribution.

#### Solution
Split param_buf into two independent streams:
  - off_buf: offset bytes only (from ALL match types: EXACT1/2/3 and DELTA1/2/3)
  - delta_buf: mtype + delta_value bytes only (from DELTA matches only)

Updated OVHD macro: `OVHD(tid, n_off, n_delta, n_len, fb)` where:
  EXACT1: n_off=1, n_delta=0, n_len=1
  EXACT2: n_off=2, n_delta=0, n_len=1
  EXACT:  n_off=3, n_delta=0, n_len=2
  DELTA1: n_off=1, n_delta=2, n_len=1   (mtype+delta=2 bytes to delta stream)
  DELTA2: n_off=2, n_delta=2, n_len=1
  DELTA:  n_off=3, n_delta=2, n_len=2

Block header: 11 fields → 13 fields (add enc_off_size, enc_delta_size, off_dec_len,
delta_dec_len). Four rANS freq tables → five (add delta table: +512 bytes per block).
Magic: ZXL9 (0x394C585A) → ZXLA (0x414C585A).

Decompressor: uses pi_off (was pi) for offset bytes, pi_delta for mtype/delta bytes.

#### Benchmark Results (ZXLA)

  ntdll.dll    : 0.4463  (was 0.4474, −1.1 pts)
  kernel32.dll : 0.4443  (was 0.4442, +0.1 pts — noise)
  user32.dll   : 0.3664  (was 0.3661, +0.3 pts — noise)

  Round-trip test: PASS

#### Analysis
Gain smaller than expected (estimated 3–5 pts, got ~1 pt on ntdll). Reasons:
  1. Delta matches are a small fraction of all tokens in post-BCJ PE files (most
     patterns become exact matches after E8/E9/Jcc conversion).
  2. mtype bytes (always 1 or 2) are few enough that their near-binary entropy
     doesn't significantly compress better separated.
  3. Offset bytes for EXACT and DELTA matches have similar distributions —
     the split doesn't dramatically change the offset model quality.
Net result: ntdll improved, kernel32/user32 effectively unchanged.

#### Updated Comparison (ZXLA)

  File          ZXLA    gzip-9   zstd-9   bzip2-9
  ntdll.dll    0.4463   0.4596   0.4442   0.4346
  kernel32.dll 0.4443   0.4574   0.4455   0.4416
  user32.dll   0.3664   0.3852   0.3630   0.3651

  ZXLA beats gzip-9 on all files.
  ZXLA beats zstd-9 on kernel32.
  ZXLA still behind zstd-9 on ntdll (gap: 2.1 pts) and user32 (gap: 3.4 pts).
  ZXLA still behind bzip2-9 on ntdll and kernel32 — bzip2 is a new target.

Note: Previous session notes incorrectly stated ZXL9 beat zstd-9 on user32. It did not
(0.3661 > 0.3630). ZXL9 only beat zstd-9 on kernel32 (0.4442 < 0.4455).

