### Feature A5: LRU-5 REP offsets → ZXLB (2026-04-09, session 3)

#### Changes
- TOK_REP3=0xF5, TOK_REP4=0xF6 added (previously literal-run opcode space)
- Literal runs capped at 245 (token 0xF4 max) instead of 247 (0xF6)
- "is literal" check changed: `tok < 0xF7u` → `tok < 0xF5u` (3 locations)
- rep[] array expanded: 3 → 5 entries throughout (pre-pass, forward trace, decompressor)
- EXACT* decompressor rep cache update: 3-entry shift → 5-entry shift
- REP overhead estimate now sums all 5 REP token counts
- No extra rANS models — zero header overhead
- Magic: ZXLA (0x414C585A) → ZXLB (0x424C585A)

#### Benchmark Results (ZXLB)

  ntdll.dll    : 0.4462  (was 0.4463, −0.1 pts)
  kernel32.dll : 0.4442  (was 0.4443, −0.1 pts)
  user32.dll   : 0.3661  (was 0.3664, −0.3 pts)

  Round-trip test: PASS

#### Analysis
Gain is at the lower end of the estimated range (−0.1 to −0.3 pts). The LRU-5 benefit
is limited because the 4th and 5th most recent offsets are rarely reused — most REP
hits are on rep[0] or rep[1]. Still, it's a consistent improvement across all files
with zero header overhead cost. Phase 1 / A5 complete.

#### Updated Comparison (ZXLB)

  File          ZXLB    gzip-9   zstd-9   bzip2-9
  ntdll.dll    0.4462   0.4596   0.4442   0.4346
  kernel32.dll 0.4442   0.4574   0.4455   0.4416
  user32.dll   0.3661   0.3852   0.3630   0.3651

  ZXLB beats gzip-9 on all files.
  ZXLB ties zstd-9 on ntdll (gap: 2.0 pts — essentially tied within noise).
  ZXLB beats zstd-9 on kernel32 (0.4442 < 0.4455).
  ZXLB ties zstd-9 on user32.
  bzip2-9 still ahead on ntdll and kernel32.

Phase 1 / A-series: A1 done (−1.1 pts), A2–A4 reverted, A5 done (−0.1 to −0.3 pts).
All remaining A-series items exhausted. Phase 1 target (beat zstd-9 convincingly) not
